{{Infobox NRHP | name = Bohemian Hall and Park | nrhp_type = | image = Bohemian Hall Astoria jeh.JPG | caption = Bohemian Hall, January 2009 | location= 29-19 24th Avenue, [[Astoria, Queens|Astoria]], [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]] 11105 | coordinates = {{coord|40|46|22|N|73|54|59|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = New York City#New York#USA | built = 1910 | architect = Chmelik, Frank | architecture = Classical Revival | added = March 23, 2001 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 01000239 <ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref> }}
The '''Bohemian Citizens' Benevolent Society''' is a private [[friendly society|benevolent society]] founded in 1892 in [[Astoria, Queens]] to support [[Czechs|Czech]] and [[Slovaks|Slovak]] [[immigrant]]s to the area, as well as people of Czech and Slovak ancestry. The Society is commonly known as "Bohemian Hall", for the historic structure ([[National Register of Historic Places listings in Queens County, New York|NRHP]]) in which it is located.<ref name="nris"/>
==Description== The founders of the organization said that the purpose of the society is to encourage, support, and maintain [[Bohemian]] schools, dramatics, and libraries for Czech children and children of Czech heritage; to maintain a non-profit-making home social for Czechs and people of [[Czech American|Czech ancestry]] in which the Czech culture may be taught and blended with American traditions and culture which makes the people better Americans.<ref name="Hidden">{{cite book | last1 = Reaven | first1 = Marci | last2 = J. Zeitlin | first2 = Steven | title = Hidden New York: a guide to places that matter | publisher = Rutgers University Press | year = 2006 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=xgOtV4Nynd0C&pg=PA44&dq=Bohemian+Citizens%27+Benevolent+Society&hl=en&ei=dOgXTKjFK8qUnAfprpjKCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Bohemian%20Citizens%27%20Benevolent%20Society&f=false | accessdate = 2010-06-15 | isbn = 978-0-8135-3890-7}}</ref> The organization has an annual revenue of [[United States dollar|$]]1,000,000 and employs a staff of approximately 14. The current president of the organization is Alan Svoboda.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.manta.com/c/mm7h30g/bohemian-citizens-benevolent-society-of-astoria-inc | title = Bohemian Citizens Benevolent Society Of Astoria Inc | accessdate = 2010-06-15 | work = Manta}}</ref><ref name="nrhpinv_ny">{{cite web|url=https://cris.parks.ny.gov/ |title=Cultural Resource Information System (CRIS) |publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]] |format=Searchable database |accessdate=2016-04-01 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Note:'' This includes {{cite web|url=https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=22164&q=false |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Bohemian Citizens' Benevolent Society |accessdate=2016-04-01 |author=Kathy Howe |format=PDF |date=December 2000 }} and [https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=22166&q=false ''Accompanying 20 photographs'']</ref>
==Bohemian Hall and Beer Garden== [[File:Inside Bohemian beer garden jeh.jpg|thumb|left|Beer garden]] The Bohemian Hall and Beer Garden has a big indoor and outdoor bar complex. The bar complex can hold 800 people and is open year-round.<ref name="Daily">{{cite web | url = http://www.nydailynews.com/lifestyle/food/2010/05/23/2010-05-23_as_astorias_bohemian_hall_turns_100_a_look_at_new_yorks_best_new_beer_gardens.html | title = As Astoria's Bohemian Hall turns 100, a look at New York's best new beer gardens | accessdate = 2010-06-15 | last = Farber | first = Jim |author2=Salamone, Gina | date = 2010-05-23 | work = New York Daily News}}</ref> Food that the bar serves is [[Czech cuisine|Czech specialties]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Marie Rovito | first1 = Lisa | title = Frommer's Great Escapes From NYC Without Wheels | publisher = John Wiley and Sons | year = 2006 | pages = 108 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9zCr40ge9_0C&pg=PA108&dq=Bohemian+Citizens%27+Benevolent+Society&hl=en&ei=dOgXTKjFK8qUnAfprpjKCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=Bohemian%20Citizens%27%20Benevolent%20Society&f=false | accessdate = 2010-06-15 | isbn = 978-0-7645-9829-6}}</ref> There is a [[lime tree]] that was planted by [[Václav Havel]].<ref name="Hidden" /> There are old signs and flags from the Czech Republic inside the bar. There are [[Beer in the Czech Republic|beers]] from the Czech Republic and Slovakia like [[Zlatý Bažant|Golden Pheasant]], [[BrouCzech]], [[Pilsner Urquell]], [[Krušovice]], [[Czechvar]], and [[Staropramen]].<ref name="Daily" /> Most of the workers speak [[Czech language|Czech]] and [[English language|English]]. Most of the regular people that are there are middle-aged and elderly immigrants. The Hall hosts holiday parties, ethnic festivals, local jazz groups, Czech rock bands, and touring acts.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Mitchell | first1 = Wendy | title = New York City's Best Dive Bars: Drinking and Diving in the Five Boroughs | publisher = Ig Publishing | year = 2003 | pages = 25 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HrG8nd6NrpYC&pg=PA25&dq=Bohemian+Citizens%27+Benevolent+Society&hl=en&ei=dOgXTKjFK8qUnAfprpjKCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Bohemian%20Citizens%27%20Benevolent%20Society&f=false | accessdate = 2010-06-15 | isbn = 978-0-9703125-3-2}}</ref> The Bohemian Hall hosts the annual Czech and Slovak festival. The hall also has a [[Sokol]] club and a Czech school. The Bohemian Hall keeps the people linked, visually and materially, to the past.<ref name="Hidden" />
===Closure=== Revenue was so low in the early 1990s that the hall threatened to close. A large group of people, not all Czech, started a "Save the Hall" meeting. [[Václav Havel]], the former president of [[Czechoslovakia]], was so moved by the outcome of the meeting that when he stopped by in 2000 he stayed for hours and held a conference.<ref name="Hidden" />
