{{for|the district|Dariganga, Sükhbaatar}} {{Refimprove|date=February 2011}} {{Infobox ethnic group |group = Dariganga Mongols |image = |pop = 27,412 |region1 = [[Mongolia]] |pop1 = 27,412 |ref1 = <ref name="mongolian">[http://www.toollogo2010.mn/doc/Main%20results_20110615_to%20EZBH_for%20print.pdf National Census 2010] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915000000/http://www.toollogo2010.mn/doc/Main%20results_20110615_to%20EZBH_for%20print.pdf |date=September 15, 2011 }}</ref> |region2 = |pop2 = |ref2 = |region3 = |pop3 = |ref3 = |languages = [[Khalkha Mongolian|Khalkha dialect]] of [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]] |religions = [[Tibetan Buddhism]], [[Shamanism]] , [[Atheism]] |related= [[Mongols]], [[Halh Mongols|Halh]], [[Chahar Mongols|Chahar]], [[Ööled]] }} The '''Dariganga''' ([[Mongolian language|Mongolian]]: Дарьганга) are an eastern [[Mongols|Mongol]] subgroup who mainly live in [[Dari Ovoo]] and [[Ganga Lake, Mongolia|Ganga Lake]], [[Sukhbaatar Province]].
It is believed{{by whom|date=February 2011}} that the Dariganga were resettled by the [[Qing Dynasty]] from [[Chahar Mongols|Chahar]], [[Khalkha]] and [[Ööled]] to herd horses of the Emperor in the late 1690s.
From 1912 on, a Ministry of Internal Affairs of the [[Boghda Khaanate of Mongolia]] supervised them. And the [[People's Republic of Mongolia]] changed their banner system in 1921. After many reforms in Mongolian administration structure, the Dariganga people have lived in the sums: Dariganga, Naran, Ongon, Khalzan, Asgat and Bayandelger of Sukhbaatar Province since 1691.
