{{about|the American sociologist|the United States Air Force colonel|Leon F. "Lee" Ellis}} '''Altis Lee Ellis''' (born March 1, 1942)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n88245961.html |title=Ellis, Lee, 1942- |website=id.loc.gov |access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> is an American sociologist who was a professor of [[sociology]] at [[Minot State University]] from 1976 to 2007. He was also an assistant and associate professor there from 1976 to 2009, after which he served as a visiting professor at the [[University of Malaya]] from 2010 to 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Lee_Ellis/info |title=Lee Ellis |website=ResearchGate |language=en |access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref> ==Education== Ellis grew up on a farm near [[Iola, Kansas]]. He received his B.A. in sociology from [[Pittsburg State University]] in [[Kansas]] in 1966, where he went on to receive his M.S. in sociology in 1970. He then received his Ph.D. in [[criminology]] from [[Florida State University]] in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mail.misu.nodak.edu/~lee.ellis/LeeWeb/vitae.html |title=Lee Ellis CV |date=2007-04-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827223825/http://mail.misu.nodak.edu/~lee.ellis/LeeWeb/vitae.html |archive-date=2008-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite thesis |last=Ellis |first=Lee |title=Androgens, the nervous system and criminal behavior |date=1984 |degree=Ph.D. |publisher=Florida State University |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/androgens-the-nervous-system-and-criminal-behavior/oclc/10881960&referer=brief_results |language=English}}</ref> ==Research== Ellis is known for researching the potential biological roots of [[sexual orientation]], and organized a conference on the subject that occurred in May 1995.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/17724/title/Biological-Determination-Of-Sexuality-Heating-Up-As-A-Research-Field/ |title=Biological Determination Of Sexuality Heating Up As A Research Field |last=Finn |first=Robert |date=1996-01-08 |website=The Scientist |access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2001/02/19/in-search-of-the-gay-gene/ecddce53-2bcc-427c-aef4-663d770056ed/ |title=In Search of the 'Gay Gene' |last=Lucentini |first=Jack |date=2001-02-19 |website=The Washington Post |language=en-US |access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref> He has also studied the potential for the use of thyroid and obesity medications during pregnancy to increase the odds of children being homosexual.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1989-01-29/lifestyle/8901280399_1_homosexuality-hormone-fluctuations-ellis-and-associates |title=Study Looks For Cause Of Homosexuality |last=Burns |first=Diane Hubbard |date=1989-01-29 |work=Orlando Sentinel |access-date=2017-12-22 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1478256/Pregnant-women-who-take-slimming-pills-are-more-likely-to-have-gay-children.html |title=Pregnant women who take slimming pills 'are more likely to have gay children' |last=Matthews|first=Robert |website=Telegraph.co.uk |language=en |access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> He has also studied numerous other topics, such as the relationships between obesity in women and the number of children they give birth to,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Science_News/2004/09/20/Study-obese-women-having-more-children/14091095712735/?spt=su |title=Study: obese women having more children |date=2004-09-20 |website=UPI |language=en |access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref> the link between left-handedness and mortality,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/feb/04/paulharris.theobserver1 |title=The Lord giveth with one hand. And it's the right one |last=Harris |first=Paul |date=2001-02-03 |website=The Guardian |language=en-GB |access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> and the effect one's genes have on the career they end up working in.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bismarcktribune.com/n